321 2027 1673 (The reasons for choosing a function syntax instead a assignment operator syntax) 1673 SB
321 2081 80 (are:) 80 SB
321 2135 52 (1. ) 59 SB
380 2135 1648 (A function syntax allows standardized hardware register addressing to be added) 1648 SB
380 2189 1648 (to the standard without the need to extend the existing native type system or the) 1648 SB
380 2243 1036 (abstract machine concept used by the C standard.) 1036 SB
321 2297 52 (2. ) 59 SB
380 2297 1616 (A function syntax still allow compilers to implement I/O register addressing with) 1616 SB
380 2351 1587 (exactly the same runtime efficiency as we have with current practice, but now) 1587 SB
380 2405 1641 (using a standardized syntax.  This can be done simply by implementing the new) 1641 SB
380 2459 1519 (I/O functions as either function like macros or with the new keyword inline.) 1519 SB
321 2513 52 (3. ) 59 SB
380 2513 896 (Functions is the C way to do encapsulation.) 896 SB
380 2567 1659 (Although the new I/O functions looks like API functions, the real purpose with the) 1659 SB
380 2621 1670 (function syntax is to provide a portable and standardized mechanism for enabling) 1670 SB
380 2675 1636 (use of the different compiler specific extended types needed for I/O access with) 1636 SB
380 2729 1431 (different kinds of processor architecture, without sacrificing portability.) 1431 SB
321 2783 52 (4. ) 59 SB
380 2783 1506 (A function syntax provides an encapsulation of the underlying addressing) 1506 SB
380 2837 1638 (method and provides a save and portable migration path for compiler support to) 1638 SB
380 2891 924 (still more advanced addressing mechanisms.) 924 SB
321 2945 52 (5. ) 59 SB
380 2945 1589 (The standard I/O functions limits the types of operation done on I/O hardware) 1589 SB
380 2999 1670 (registers to the native access operations \(read, write\) which can be accomplished) 1670 SB
380 3053 1650 (on I/O registers with all embedded processor architectures, plus I/O functions for) 1650 SB
