321 733 1093 (The reason for using a new abstract access type are:) 1093 SB
321 787 52 (1. ) 59 SB
380 787 1583 (The new type provides a uniform and portable mechanism for referencing I/O) 1583 SB
380 841 629 (registers in the C source code.) 629 SB
321 895 52 (2. ) 59 SB
380 895 1617 (The abstract access_type provides a standardized method to isolate the actual) 1617 SB
380 949 1608 (addressing method used by a given I/O register with a given processor system) 1608 SB
380 1003 1521 (from the C source code itself.  In effect it enables a programmer to write C) 1521 SB
380 1057 1601 (source code with hardware addressing operations in a compiler \(and platform\)) 1601 SB
380 1111 440 (independent manner.) 440 SB
321 1165 52 (3. ) 59 SB
380 1165 1500 (It is a continuation of good programming practice, where I/O registers are) 1500 SB
380 1219 1651 (identified by symbolic names instead of physical addresses, and where symbolic) 1651 SB
380 1273 1657 (names for I/O registers are defined in separate header files, to order to make the) 1657 SB
380 1327 959 (source code itself more readable and portable.) 959 SB
321 1381 52 (4. ) 59 SB
380 1381 1519 (The access definition encapsulation provides a uniform, safe and portable) 1519 SB
380 1435 1639 (migration path for the implementation of still more advanced compiler supported) 1639 SB
380 1489 1464 (access mechanisms.  For instance from direct-addressing over indirect-) 1464 SB
380 1543 1575 (addressing to addressing via different access drivers and the use of different) 1575 SB
380 1597 382 (mapping methods.) 382 SB
321 1651 52 (5. ) 59 SB
